# CLAUDE.md

This file provides guidance to Claude Code when working with code in this repository.

## Project Overview

Cross-platform C++ SDK wrapped as an Apple XCFramework, exposing a pure C-ABI
so the same compiled library can later be consumed from Android (`.aar`),
Windows (`.dll`), or any other C-capable host without C++ ABI coupling.

## Architecture

```
{{SDK_NAME}}/            C++17 CMake library -> builds as .framework per platform slice
  include/                 C-ABI public header (no STL, no exceptions cross the line)
  src/                     C++ implementation (STL/templates/Pimpl free to use here)
  framework/module.modulemap  Clang module map injected post-build so Swift can import {{SDK_NAME}}
  tools/smoke_test.cpp   standalone CLI sanity check (skipped when cross-compiling for iOS)

build_xcframework.sh    builds 3 slices (macOS fat, iOS device arm64, iOS sim fat),
                        assembles them into {{SDK_NAME}}.xcframework at repo root

{{SDK_NAME}}.xcframework/   output artifact; consumed by a Swift client via ../{{SDK_NAME}}.xcframework
```

## Build Commands

**Build {{SDK_NAME}}.xcframework** (run from repo root):
```bash
./build_xcframework.sh
```

**Build for macOS only** (faster iteration):
```bash
cmake -S {{SDK_NAME}} -B {{SDK_NAME}}/build-macos -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release \
      -DCMAKE_OSX_ARCHITECTURES="arm64;x86_64"
cmake --build {{SDK_NAME}}/build-macos --target {{SDK_NAME}}
```

**Run smoke test** (macOS only):
```bash
cmake --build {{SDK_NAME}}/build-macos --target {{SDK_NAME_LOWER}}_smoke_test
./{{SDK_NAME}}/build-macos/{{SDK_NAME_LOWER}}_smoke_test
```

## C++ Architecture Principles

**C-ABI boundary** -- `include/{{SDK_NAME}}.h` is pure C: no STL types, no
exceptions, no C++ references crossing the boundary. POD structs only, with
a leading `struct_size` field on anything likely to grow, so the layout can
change without breaking older consumers.

**Pimpl idiom** -- concrete classes (`{{ENTITY_NAME}}Manager`, `{{ENTITY_NAME}}Session`) hide their
implementation behind `class Impl`. The destructor is declared in the `.h`
and defined in the `.cpp` (where `Impl` is complete), keeping `unique_ptr<Impl>`
working with an incomplete type in the header.

**Pure abstract interfaces** (`I{{CHANNEL_NAME}}`) -- code above the interface never
holds a pointer to the concrete backend, only to `I{{CHANNEL_NAME}}`. This makes
swapping in a real hardware backend, a mock for tests, or a replay backend a
matter of adding one class, not touching call sites.

**Factory as the single creation point** -- `{{CHANNEL_NAME}}Factory::Create({{CHANNEL_NAME}}Mode)` is the
only place that instantiates a concrete `I{{CHANNEL_NAME}}`. Callers never `new` one directly.

**Async via `std::function` callbacks** -- samples, state changes, and errors
are pushed to the caller via registered callbacks. Worker threads use
`std::atomic<bool>` for the stop flag and `join()` on stop/destruction.
`Simulator{{CHANNEL_NAME}}` serializes callback registration against
invocation with `callbackMu_`, held for the whole invocation -- this makes
`setXCallback(nullptr)` an unsubscription barrier: it won't return while a
callback is mid-flight, so once it does, freeing the `user_data` the
callback closed over is safe. Never call a `setXCallback` from inside a
callback body -- self-deadlock.

**Exception barrier at the C-ABI facade** -- every `extern "C"` function in
`capi/{{ENTITY_NAME_LOWER}}_c_api.cpp` runs its body through `guardedVoid()`
or `guardedRef<Ref>()`. A C++ exception escaping an `extern "C"` function is
undefined behavior for a Swift/plain-C caller with no matching unwinder;
`new`, `std::string`/`std::function` construction, and
`std::thread::join()` (in a Pimpl destructor) are all real throw sources,
not hypothetical ones.

**`Simulator{{CHANNEL_NAME}}` simulates real failures** -- it is not a toy stub; extend it
to fabricate the failure modes your real hardware has (link drops,
reconnects, jitter, low battery, ...) so UI and app code can be built and
tested before hardware backend exists.

## Key Constraints

- Public header in `include/` must remain pure C: no STL types, no C++
  exceptions, no C++ references. Structs should be POD.
- `framework/module.modulemap` is hand-maintained and injected via a CMake
  post-build step -- keep it in sync when the public header changes.
- Deployment targets: macOS {{DEPLOYMENT_TARGET_MACOS}}, iOS {{DEPLOYMENT_TARGET_IOS}} (defined in `build_xcframework.sh`).
